{"title_page": "Bernard Malgrange", "text_new": "{{short description|French mathematician}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Bernard Malgrange\n| image             = Bernard Malgrange.jpeg\n| image_size        = 200px\n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1928|07|06|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = [[Paris]]\n| death_date        = \n| death_place       = \n| nationality       = French\n| fields            = [[Mathematics]]\n| workplaces        = \n| alma_mater        = [[Universit\u00e9 Henri Poincar\u00e9]]\n| doctoral_advisor  = [[Laurent Schwartz]]\n| doctoral_students = [[M. Salah Baouendi]]\n| known_for         = [[Ehrenpreis\u2013Malgrange theorem]]<br>[[Malgrange preparation theorem]]\n| awards            = \n}}\n'''Bernard Malgrange''' (born 6 July 1928) is a [[France|French]] [[mathematician]] who works on [[differential equation]]s and [[singularity theory]]. He proved the [[Ehrenpreis\u2013Malgrange theorem]] and the [[Malgrange preparation theorem]], essential for the classification theorem of the elementary [[catastrophe theory|catastrophes]] of [[Ren\u00e9 Thom]]. He received his [[Ph.D.]] from [[Universit\u00e9 Henri Poincar\u00e9]] (Nancy 1) in 1955. His advisor was [[Laurent Schwartz]]. He was elected to the [[Acad\u00e9mie des sciences]] in 1988. In 2012 he gave the [[\u0141ojasiewicz Lecture]] (on the \"Differential algebraic groups\") at the [[Jagiellonian University|Jagiellonian University in Krak\u00f3w]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.im.uj.edu.pl/en_GB/lojasiewicz/2012|title=2012 Lecture - Institute of Mathematics of the Jagiellonian University|website=www.im.uj.edu.pl|access-date=2016-12-29}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n*''Ideals of differentiable functions'' (Oxford University Press, 1966)\n*''\u00c9quations diff\u00e9rentielles \u00e0 coefficients polynomiaux'', Progress in Mathematics (Birkh\u00e4user, 1991).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MathGenealogy |id=59394}}\n* Acad\u00e9mie des sciences page on [https://web.archive.org/web/20061125221418/http://www.academie-sciences.fr/membres/M/Malgrange_Bernard_notice.htm Bernard Malgrange]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Malgrange, Bernard}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:\u00c9cole Normale Sup\u00e9rieure alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century French mathematicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century French mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the French Academy of Sciences]]\n\n\n{{france-mathematician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French mathematician}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Bernard Malgrange\n| image             = Bernard Malgrange.jpeg\n| image_size        = 200px\n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1928|07|06|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = [[Paris]]\n| death_date        = \n| death_place       = \n| nationality       = French\n| fields            = [[Mathematics]]\n| workplaces        = \n| alma_mater        = [[Universit\u00e9 Henri Poincar\u00e9]]\n| doctoral_advisor  = [[Laurent Schwartz]]\n| doctoral_students = [[M. Salah Baouendi]]\n| known_for         = [[Ehrenpreis\u2013Malgrange theorem]]<br>[[Malgrange preparation theorem]]\n| awards            = \n}}\n'''Bernard Malgrange''' (born 6 July 1928) is a [[France|French]] [[mathematician]] who works on [[differential equation]]s and [[singularity theory]]. He proved the [[Ehrenpreis\u2013Malgrange theorem]] and the [[Malgrange preparation theorem]], essential for the classification theorem of the elementary [[catastrophes]] of [[Ren\u00e9 Thom]]. He received his [[Ph.D.]] from [[Universit\u00e9 Henri Poincar\u00e9]] (Nancy 1) in 1955. His advisor was [[Laurent Schwartz]]. He was elected to the [[Acad\u00e9mie des sciences]] in 1988. In 2012 he gave the [[\u0141ojasiewicz Lecture]] (on the \"Differential algebraic groups\") at the [[Jagiellonian University|Jagiellonian University in Krak\u00f3w]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.im.uj.edu.pl/en_GB/lojasiewicz/2012|title=2012 Lecture - Institute of Mathematics of the Jagiellonian University|website=www.im.uj.edu.pl|access-date=2016-12-29}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n*''Ideals of differentiable functions'' (Oxford University Press, 1966)\n*''\u00c9quations diff\u00e9rentielles \u00e0 coefficients polynomiaux'', Progress in Mathematics (Birkh\u00e4user, 1991).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MathGenealogy |id=59394}}\n* Acad\u00e9mie des sciences page on [https://web.archive.org/web/20061125221418/http://www.academie-sciences.fr/membres/M/Malgrange_Bernard_notice.htm Bernard Malgrange]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Malgrange, Bernard}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:\u00c9cole Normale Sup\u00e9rieure alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century French mathematicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century French mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the French Academy of Sciences]]\n\n\n{{france-mathematician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Cnwilliams", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:catastrophes\u2192catastrophe theory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernard_Malgrange"}
